Question 2

# Categorizing flight times
time_category <- function(time) {
  if (is.na(time)) return(NA)
  hour <- floor(time / 100)
  if (hour >= 0 & hour < 6) {
    return("early morning")
  } else if (hour >= 6 & hour < 12) {
    return("morning")
  } else if (hour >= 12 & hour < 18) {
    return("afternoon")
  } else {
    return("evening")
  }
}

# Creating categorical variables
flights_time <- flights %>%
  mutate(
    flight_dep = sapply(dep_time, time_category),
    flight_arr = sapply(arr_time, time_category)
  )
# Departure Time Barplot
ggplot(flights_time %>% filter(!is.na(flight_dep))) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = flight_dep, fill = flight_dep)) +
  labs(title = "Flights by Departure Time",
       fill = "Time Category",
       x = "Departure Time",
       y = "# of Flights")
# Arrival Time Barplot
ggplot(flights_time %>% filter(!is.na(flight_arr))) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = flight_arr, fill = flight_arr)) +
             labs(title = "Flights by Arrival Time",
                  fill = "Time Category",
                  x = "Arrival Time",
                  y = "# of Flights") 
# Calculating "red eye" flights
red_eye <- flights_time %>%
  filter(flight_dep %in% c("afternoon", "evening") &
           flight_arr %in% c("early morning", "morning"))

percent_red_eye <- nrow(red_eye) / nrow(flights_time) * 100

percent_red_eye
[1] 3.157291

Interpretation: After removing NAs, most flights departed either in the afternoon or morning and majority arrived in the evening.

Approximately 3.16% of flights were red eye flights, indicating that a relatively small but noticeable portion of flights depart later in the day and arrive early in the morning.

Answer: There are 3 duplicated keys, meaning there are 3 different set of variable combinations that appear more than once. There are 6 duplicated rows, meaning among those 3 keys, there are 6 extra rows in total.

After taking a closer look at the 6 rows, there are two rows for the same year, month, day, hour, and origin, specifically the date 11/3/2013 at each airport. After a Google search, daylight savings ended on that date, so the clocks were set back one hour. Therefore, the 1:00am hour (1) happened twice, once in daylight savings time and once in standard time. Because two weather observations were recorded, when pasted together, the hours look the same. The variable time_hour can fix this glitch, which is why this tidy data set gives almost enough information.

# Merging the flights and weather data sets
flights_weather <- flights %>%

To answer the primary question, the key outcome is dep_delay since it tells us how late the flight left. An alternative outcome variable to look at is arr_delay, how late the flight arrived. Additionally, origin and carrier can be helpful when identifying if some airlines are more likely to have a delay.

Since the question is asking about weather phenomena, important variables to consider that can impact flight times are temp (especially extreme temperatures), dewp (humidity & fog), wind_speed, precip (rain/snow), and visib. Time-related variables such as month, day, and hour are important to provide context for delays such as seasonal weather patterns.

  • Numeric variables are dep_delay, arr_delay, temp, dewp, humid, wind_speed, precip, visib
  • Categorical variables are origin, carrier, month, day, and hour

Interpretation: By looking at the distribution of departure delays, most of the departure times were only delayed by a few minutes, given the strong right-skew of the histogram. However, there is quite a long, extended tail towards longer delays, indicating that some flights did experience significant delays.

The distribution of precipitation is heavily right-skewed, with most values condensed towards 0. There are only a few observations showing some precipitation. Therefore, most flights departed in dry conditions, but the rare cases of precipitation may influence delay times, making it an important variable to look at.

The wind speed distribution has a slight skewed distribution centered at 10 mph, with moments of higher speeds. After a Google search, departing flights are impacted by wind speeds exceeding 35-40 mph, which only happened a few times, however, the presence of wind can still impact takeoff/landing.

Visibility, on the other hand, has a big left skew with values condensed towards 10 miles, but there are observations at lower visibility. Thus, while low visibility was not common, it can still have an impact on flight delays.

Question 9

To answer the primary question, departure delay (dep_delay) will be the main outcome. From the weather data set, typical variables that can impact delays are temperature, dew point, humidity, wind direction, wind speed, precipitation, visibility, and pressure. From Question 6, wind gust had more than 50% NAs, so this variable will not be included in the analysis.

First, letâs see the correlations between the weather variables and departure delay.

# Filter NAs and remove wind_gust to fit in regression model
model_data <- flights_weather %>%
  filter(!is.na(dep_delay), !is.na(temp), !is.na(visib), !is.na(precip), !is.na(pressure), !is.na(wind_speed)) %>%
  select(dep_delay, temp, dewp, humid, wind_speed, precip, pressure, visib)

lm_model <- lm(dep_delay ~ temp + dewp + humid + wind_speed + precip + pressure + visib, data = model_data)

According to effect sizes, precipitation is the most practical predictor (coefficient of 73) followed by visibility and pressure (for their direction mainly). # Convert continuous weather variables into categories and visual plot

# Precipitation
precip_summary <- flights_weather %>%
  mutate(
    precip_cat = case_when(
      precip == 0 ~ "None",
      precip > 0 & precip <= 0.05 ~ "Light",
      precip > 0.05 & precip <= 0.20 ~ "Moderate",
      precip > 0.20 & precip <= 0.50 ~ "Heavy",
      precip > 0.50 ~ "Extreme"
    )
  ) %>%
  group_by(precip_cat) %>%
  summarise(
    n_flights = n(),
    avg_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    pct_flights = n_flights / nrow(flights_weather) * 100,
    .groups = "drop"
  )

print(precip_summary)

Interpretation: The initial correlations were misleading because they only measured linear relationships, thus by breaking down relevant variables and calculating th average delay within each category, there is a threshold effect that causes delays. Also, categorizing numerical values into essentially low, medium, and high groups, helps in figuring out what degree of each variable is responsible for departure delays. Estimating the value ranges for each variable were decided based on online research.

Looking at the biggest average delay for each weather variable, NYC airports experienced an average 48 min departure delay when precipitation is extreme, an average 30 min delay when visibility is poor (1-5 miles), an average 18 min delay when wind speeds are severe (>= 30 mph), an average 19 min delay when temperatures are warm (75-90F), an average 20 min delay when relative humidity is high (> 60%), and an average 19 min delay when pressure is low (< 1010 mb). After doing some research online, New York, in general, tends to have higher humidity during the summer, so it is important to note that the results from relatively humidity might be due to geography.

In conclusion, the weather phenomena that has the most impact on flight delays in 2013 for NYC airports are extreme precipitation, low visibility, severe wind speeds, and warm temperatures with precipitation having the longest impact. Humidity and pressure serves as a signal for the top factors. For example, low pressure indicates severe weather like high winds and high humidity is a precursor for low visibility (fog formation).
